Rule 1016/17 (Power=2)
Activity Levels

      Activity is a stuck player switch with values active and
      inactive.

      "Off hold" and "on hold" are unambiguous synonyms for "active"
      and "inactive", respectively.

      A player may flip eir activity, unless e has done so within the
      past week.

      Inactive players may not vote, make proposals, hold office, or
      be a judge of a CFJ.  An inactive player may not be required by
      the rules to perform any duty or action, unless the rules
      explicitly state that they can require inactive players to
      perform that duty or action.

      This rule takes precedence over all other rules that regulate
      activity, or the powers or duties that a player may have because
      of eir activity.

Rule 2076/0 (Power=1)
Card cards

       The following classes of cards are defined:

       Caption:  Your Turn
       Elements: Budgeted
       Exploit:  A Player you name must play or discard a card in the
                 next 72 hours, or commit the Class-1 Infraction of
                 Delay of Game, reportable by you.

========================================================================

Judge root's Arguments:

The text of Your Turn reads:

      A Player you name must play or discard a card in the
      next 72 hours, or commit the Class-1 Infraction of
      Delay of Game, reportable by you.

I do not find that this text poses an ultimatum, as the caller argues.
It does *not* read along the lines of:

      A Player you name commits the Class-1 Infraction of
      Delay of Game, reportable by you, unless e plays or
      discards a card in the next 72 hours.

If the rule did read this way, this judge would still find that the
rule imposes a requirement due to the very nature of Infractions and
Crimes, but it does not.

Rather, this rule clearly gives the targeted player three options
and requires em to perform one.  E can play a card within 72 hours, e
can discard a card within 72 hours, or e can commit the Infraction of
Delay of Game.

Here comes the tricky part:  how does e commit the Infraction?  Rule
1503/5 tells us that "an action or inaction is a Crime or an Infraction
only if defined as such by the Rules."  The Your Turn card does not
define what action or inaction constitutes the Delay of Game Infraction; it
merely gives the targeted player the option of committing it rather
than playing or discarding.  In fact, Delay of Game is not defined by
the rules.  Therefore, by R1503/5 it is not a Crime or Infraction, and
hence it may not be committed.  The statement is therefore trivially
FALSE.

